values:
So Friday night was pretty awesome, up until the very end when it was utterly horrible, which managed to overcome&nbsp;what awesomeness&nbsp;my night had previously held. Of the five people who were so anxious to take me out on my 21 run, two called to sing me happy birthday and tell me they couldnt make it, two just plain forgot and i haven't heard from them yet, and the fifth who did remember, well, we had a pretty good time until I made some drunken comment about how everyone wants to get laid on their birthday and he drunkenly took it as a hint and thought that I was going to go home with him. When I sent a text message to a friend of mine, who incidentally I'm growing unfortunately attached to, he got upset with me for 'hanging out with him and texting some other guy.' Needless to say it was all very awkward and very uncomfortable and I ended up taking a cab home, drunk, miserable and alone.

It gets better. Last night a guy I'd had a brief "thing" with, as I can't really call it anything else, and told me that the thing he appreciated about me the most was that I was exactly who and what I was and that there was never any game with me, and that I was always totally sincere and unapologetically honest about how I felt. This upset me because that very candor is the reason why he broke it off with me in the first place. Dick. "But it's ok, Ari, you'll just be one of those people who are well-loved in retrospect."&nbsp;

Today the Seahawks lost to the Steelers 21 to nil. The rest of my week will be abismal.&nbsp;

I've talked to several people about this situation with the friend I've become attached to, and they all seem to agree that I should talk to him about how I feel. I don't think this is a good idea, considering every time we've been together he's had some amount of alcohol in him. Yeah, I guess the prospect of sleeping with me is so horrible he has to be drunk to do it. Or maybe he's&nbsp;so much of pussy that he needs&nbsp;the little liquid courage. Yeah, Ari, wishfull thinking, that's what you need.&nbsp;But I can't complain, nor can I call myself a victim, if only for the fact that I'm a willing participant in my own psychological torture. Way to go, Ari, this is really good for you, keep up the awesome work.

Boys make me crazy.

Woohoo first day of school. Yippee. This day marks the beginning of 8 months of&nbsp;intellectual torture and&nbsp;extroardinary&nbsp;psychological stress. Awesome.

Still nothing from Craig. I&nbsp;am rather annoyed with myself&nbsp;for so stubbornly clinging to the hope that he might still call me, despite the fact that&nbsp;I know it's&nbsp;a hopeless cause. I guess it just gives me an excuse to be glum, as if I need more of those.&nbsp;

I've begun planning out a work schedule for a map of&nbsp;Ireland.&nbsp;I haven't decided whether it will be a map of modern day Ireland with the outlines of the counties, or a map of a more medieval Ireland with all the crazy Gaelic/Celtic&nbsp;regions instead.&nbsp;I've found the motto, which will be a cool addition to the border which, if all goes as planned, will be an amazing celticy knotty looking&nbsp;"tree of life" thing that is growing around the edges of the map, especially once I get good enough at calligraphy. I'm having trouble with the compass rose, however, but I don't forsee that being a particular problem.&nbsp;I've got until Winter break, so I should be ok. Unfortunately,&nbsp;I think this is&nbsp;the result of what I am beginning to feel is an unhealthy trend, but you're right, that's never stopped me before.&nbsp;Awesome.

I'm sick of being "the smart one." Seriously, I'm really starting to hate it. I went to a party last night&nbsp;where I&nbsp;was talking to this guy who asked me if I'd met a girl named Antigone. I had, and I mentioned off handedly that she had one of the most unfortunate names I'd ever&nbsp;heard in my life. He was flabergasted.&nbsp;"That's one of the most beautiful names I've ever heard!" he replied aghast. "Yeah, but she's named after a character who--" "But no one knows that!" he interrupted. "To everyone else&nbsp;it's something Shakespearean and cool," he added gesticulating vaguely. "Actually, I believe that was&nbsp;Sophocles," I replied blandly, supressing smirk. His eyes widened and he laughed. "Oho! We're dealing with a smart one here!"&nbsp; 

It pisses me off that guys are always so surprised when I open my mouth and say something that ought to be common knowledge. Seriously, saying that the English "gave" Israel to the Jews after WWII is not a stroke of utter genius; saying the words "the" and "French" and "Revolution" in a single breath is not brilliance; knowing the difference between "roughing the passer" and "pass interference" does not make me some sort of sports guru; nor does being able to speak about a given subject for more than five seconds with some understanding make me some sort of academic prodigy. I'm smart, not brilliant. I'm down to earth, not wise. To say that you've never met anyone like me because I'm intelligent and grounded is sad for your sake, if not for the world's, not complimentary for mine. I'm nothing particularly&nbsp;special, it's just that so many people around me are total fuck-wits. Why do people keep building me up as if I'm so amazing?&nbsp; 

I need a good rant session. I think that would cheer me up a lot.
